<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. Description of the Country around Lakes Superior and Huron, 1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0018</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">Of the Islands opposite La Pointe ten or twelve have been Visited by the Indians some of which <span class="AddHand-author">h</span>a<span class="DelHand-author">r</span><span class="AddHand-author">v</span>e a Rich Soil covered with Oak and Beech &amp; round all of which there is deep water and fine fishing for Trout<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The trout in this part of the Lake are equal to those of Mackinac in Size and richeness<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  I myself Saw one taken off the Northeast end of Montreal Island which weighed fifty two pounds<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Of how many Islands this Archipelago actually consists will not be easily assertained; but I take Carribou Island to be the eastern end of the chain.  It lies a little to the Southard of the course of the C<sup>os</sup> Vessel is about three miles Round has a flat shore and good Anchorage and is allowed to be half passage from Camanitiquia to S<sup>t</sup> Mary's.  However no other land is Seen from it by the Vessel; but that may be owing to the Islands being low and lying too much to the Southard of her course<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  It is to be observed this Acc<sup>t</sup> of the number of Islands is upon Indian authority, which tho not the best, is Still less Apocryphal than that of the Canadians<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
